<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="1122" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1122">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.6363/47.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-01">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 1, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: In thanking you for
                            your note of this day’s date on the subject of the neutralisation of the
                            oil wells, I wish to state that I quite concur in your suggestion to
                            treat the question of the control of the cities independently to that of
                            the oil wells. As you say, it is most important that there should not be
                            delay, for any delay is especially dangerous to the wells. But it is of
                            course of the utmost importance when the time comes that whoever is in
                            control of the towns should clearly understand that proper respect must
                            be paid to the principles of international law and the property of
                            neutrals.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>